title: Lyft prepares for IPO as investors weigh profitability concerns
text: Car ride sharing company Lyft is set to start trading this week. Eliot Brown, WSJ, and CNBC's Deirdre Bosa join 'The Exchange' to discuss if getting in on Lyft's IPO could be a losing investment.

title: Kevin O'Leary says Fed has no reason to cut interest rates
text: Meghan Shue, Wilmington Trust senior investment strategist, and Kevin O'Leary, O'Shares ETFs chairman, joins CNBC's "The Fast Money Halftime Report" team to discuss the recession concerns weighing on the market.

title: Lyft to prices shares above targeted range for IPO
text: CNBC's Morgan Brennan reports on news from the Wall Street Journal that Lyft will price its shares about the targeted $62-$68 range.

title: Bank stocks, energy, retailers among market leaders
text: CNBC's Bob Pisani looks ahead at the day's market action.

title: Uber buying Careem for $3.1 billion
text: Scott Gamm of Yahoo Finance breaks deal what Uber purchasing Careem means as Uber looks to go public.

title: Tech investor Ann Winblad talks Uber's Careem acquisition
text: Legendary tech investor Ann Winblad, founder and managing partner at Hummer Windblad Venture Partners, joins "Squawk Box" to discuss the latest tech ventures and anticipated IPOs including Apple TV+ and Uber's acquisition of its Middle Eastern rival Careem.

title: The yield curve is signalling slowdown: Strategist
text: The ten-year yield trading near 2019 lows, while stocks are near highs. James Camp, managing director of strategic income at Eagle Asset Management, and Scott Nations, president and chief investment officer of Nations Shares, join "Squawk Box" to discuss what this means for investors.

title: Fleming: There's still a huge supply problem in the housing market
text: Mark Fleming, chief economist at First American, discusses what this week's housing data will signal about the market and the broader U.S. economy.

title: A China trade deal the next catalyst for market growth?
text: Wells Fargo Asset Manager Ann Miletti on the impact of a potential U.S. trade deal with China on the markets, Federal Reserve policy and the outlook for stocks.

title: Uber to buy Middle East rival Careem for $3.1 billion
text: Careem CEO Mudassir Sheikha will stay on to lead the business, and both companies will continue to operate as independent brands.

title: WeWork's revenue and net losses both doubled in 2018
text: CNBC's Deirdre Bosa reports on WeWork's financial report for 2018.

title: ZipRecruiter CEO responds to Andrew Yang's criticism on AI
text: ZipRecruiter CEO Ian Siegel discusses how his company is using artificial intelligence to help match job seekers with employers and responds to 2020 presidential candidate Andrew Yang’s criticism that AI will hurt the job market.

title: Inverted yield curve doesn't guarantee recession, says market strategist
text: Tony Dwyer, chief market strategist at Canaccord Genuity, and CNBC's Mike Santoli discuss market trends and what the yield curve may or may not indicate on CNBC's "Closing Bell" team.

title: Panera and Krispy Kreme's owners admit ties to Nazi past
text: The Reimann Family which controls the consumer goods conglomerate JAB Holdings found past family members had ties to the Nazis.

title: Here's the Sackler family's statement on Purdue Pharma's $270 million settlement with Oklahoma
text: CNBC's Aditi Roy reports on coverage of the press conference following the OxyContin maker Purdue Pharma's opioid settlement with Oklahoma attorney general.

title: Seek Out New Issues With Strong Sales Growth Working On IPO Bases
text: IPO stocks can be the source of strong gains, but it’s important to first wait for an IPO base to form before buying. We’re seeing Futu Holdings starting to form an IPO base.
